# Hexagonal Architecture (Ports & Adapters)

Dependency rule: `infrastructure -> application -> domain`. Never the other way. ArchUnit (`HexagonalArchitectureTest`) fails the build on violations.

## Where things go

| Code | Package |
| --- | --- |
| Aggregates, value objects | `domain.model` |
| Ranking criteria, domain services | `domain.ranking` |
| Primary ports (use case interfaces) | `application.port.in` |
| Secondary ports (repository interfaces) | `application.port.out` |
| Use case implementations + commands | `application.usecase` |
| Controllers, request/response DTOs, REST mapper, error handling | `infrastructure.rest` |
| Mongo documents, Spring Data repos, persistence mapper | `infrastructure.persistence.mongo` |
| Bean wiring, seed | `infrastructure.configuration` |

## Rules

- `domain` and `application` classes have ZERO Spring/Mongo imports and no annotations. They are plain Java wired as beans in `ProductRankingConfiguration`:

```java
@Bean
public RankProductsUseCase rankProductsUseCase(ProductRepository repo, ProductRankingService service) {
    return new RankProductsService(repo, service);
}
```

- Controllers depend on the port (`RankProductsUseCase`), never on the implementation.
- Domain objects never leak raw infrastructure types; mappers (`ProductRankingRestMapper`, `ProductMongoMapper`) translate at each boundary.
- New use case = port interface in `port.in` + `final` service implementing it + immutable `*Command` + bean in configuration.
- If you add an architectural constraint, also add the corresponding ArchUnit test.
